Based on the task requirements and the search results, I'll start by executing the network_fetcher tool to retrieve the API data. This is the first logical step in the workflow.

<tool_call>network_fetcher
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Since the network_fetcher failed with an INVALID_RESPONSE error and the tool info doesn't suggest any specific parameter adjustments that would help, I'll try the same request again with a longer timeout and fewer retries, as these are the only adjustable parameters available.

<tool_call>network_fetcher
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "timeout": 60,
  "retry_count": 1,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Since the network_fetcher continues to fail, I'll proceed to the next step in the workflow which involves data processing, even though we don't have the API data. I'll use the data_processing_parser tool with a default input file path as specified in the task requirements.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            Since the data_processing_parser executed successfully, I'll now proceed with the next step in the workflow which is data transformation. I'll use the data_processing_transformer tool to process the output from the previous step.

<tool_call>data_processing_transformer
{
  "source": "data/output.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>
